    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 9.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "The families of the north",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 1:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", note). ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And Nebuchadnezzar the king of Babylon, my servant.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " This is the rendering of the Targum, the Syriac, and the Vulgate, and corresponds with the reading of a few extant manuscripts. The received text, however, reads, \"and unto Nebuchadnezzar,\" etc. Neither reading is satisfactory. The latter one is intolerably harsh; the former makes Nebuchadnezzar a mere adjunct of the tribes of the north. In the other passages, moreover, where this king is solemnly entitled \"my servant,\" the clause is the most prominent one in the sentence (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 27:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 43:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The words in question have a sort of family resemblance to the glosses which meet us occasionally both in the form of the Hebrew text represented by the Massoretic recension, and those by the principal ancient versions. The words are omitted by the Septuagint. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "My servant",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Generally to be a \"servant\" of Jehovah or of any supposed deity is to be a worshipper. Thus Daniel is called by Darius, \"servant of the living God\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Daniel 6:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and thus Abdallah, \"servant of Allah,\" has become a favorite surname of the followers of Mohammed. In the Book of Jeremiah itself (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 30:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 46:27, 28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and in Ezekiel (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 37:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), \"my servant\" is the form in which Jehovah addresses his chosen people; and in the second part of Isaiah the suffering Messiah is so styled. Here, however, a foreign king is thus entitled. How is this to be explained? Cyrus, no doubt, in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 44:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", 45:1, is called \"my shepherd\" and \"my anointed one;\" but then Cyrus, in the view of the prophet, was a genuine though unconscious worshipper of the true God (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 41:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), whereas Nebuchadnezzar was known to be a polytheist and an idolater. We must, therefore, take \"servant\" to be applied to Nebuchadnezzar in a lower sense than to the other bearers of the title. The Hebrew 'ebbed, in fact, may be either \"slave\" in something approaching to the terrible modern sense, or in the sense in which Eliezer was one (i.e. little less than a son, and a possible heir, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 24:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Galatians 4:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and which is still in full force in Arabia. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "An astonishment",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (see on Jeremiah 2:11). ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "An hissing",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 18:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 19:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Jeremiah 25:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "For this obstinate resistance the Lord will cause the nations of the north, under Nebuchadrezzar's leadership, to come and lay Judah waste. \"All the families of the north\" points back to all the tribes of the kingdoms of the north, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 1:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ואל נבוך cannot be joined with \"and take,\" but must depend from שׁלח in such a way that that verb is again repeated in thought. Ew. proposes to read ואת according to some codd., especially as Syr., Chald., Vulg. have rendered by an accusative. Against this Graf has justly objected, that then Nebuchadnezzar would be merely mentioned by the way as in addition to the various races, whereas it is he that brings these races and is the instrument of destruction in God's hand. Ew.'s reading is therefore to be unhesitatingly rejected. No valid reason appears for pronouncing the words: and to Nebuchadrezzar...my servant, to be a later interpolation (Hitz., Gr.) because they are not in the lxx. There is prominence given to Nebuchadnezzar by the very change of the construction, another \"send\" requiring to be repeated before \"to Nebuchadrezzar.\" God calls Nebuchadnezzar His servant, as the executor of His will on Judah, cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 27:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 43:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The \"them\" in \"and bring them\" refers to Nebuchadnezzar and the races of the north. \"This land\" is Judah, the הזּאת being δεικτικῶς; so too the corresponding האלּה, \"all these peoples round about;\" so that we need have no doubt of the genuineness of the demonstrative. The peoples meant are those found about Judah, that are specified in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 25:19-25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". החרמתּים, used frequently in Deuteronomy and Joshua for the extirpation of the Canaanites, is used by Jeremiah, besides here, only in the prophecy against Babylon, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 50:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 50:26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 51:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". With לשׁמּה ולשׁרקה cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 19:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 18:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; the words cannot be used of the peoples, but of the countries, which have been comprehended in the mention of the peoples. With \"everlasting desolations,\" cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 49:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 58:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 61:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". - With ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 25:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 16:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 7:34",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". But here the thought is strengthened by the addition: the sound of the mill and the light of the lamp. Not merely every sound of joyfulness shall vanish, but even every sign of life, such as could make known the presence of inhabitants. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]